{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584800"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:57:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.39,0.23,0.03,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116177"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7496"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98173"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7660"},{"type":"tags","id":"7871"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18576"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116177"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMyelodysplastic syndromes are acquired disorders of haematopoietic stem cells characterized by ineffective blood cell production and risk of progression to acute myeloid leukaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of anaemia is most commonly associated with myelodysplastic syndromes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Microcytic anaemia","Aplastic anaemia","Normocytic anaemia","Haemolytic anaemia","Macrocytic anaemia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrocytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most characteristic type of anaemia seen in myelodysplastic syndromes. This occurs due to defective DNA synthesis and maturation in erythroid precursors, leading to larger than normal red blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicrocytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in iron deficiency or thalassaemia, not in myelodysplastic syndromes. \u003Cstrong\u003EAplastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E represents complete bone marrow failure rather than the dysplastic changes seen in myelodysplastic syndromes. \u003Cstrong\u003ENormocytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in myelodysplastic syndromes but is less common than macrocytic anaemia. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E involves increased destruction of red blood cells, which is not a primary feature of myelodysplastic syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe macrocytosis in myelodysplastic syndromes reflects the underlying pathophysiology of ineffective erythropoiesis and dysplastic changes in the bone marrow.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Myelodysplastic syndromes (MDS) typically present with macrocytic anaemia due to ineffective erythropoiesis.","The macrocytosis in MDS results from dysplastic changes in red blood cell precursors.","MDS is a bone marrow disorder characterized by cytopenias and morphological abnormalities in blood cells."],"references":["Li H, Hu F, Gale RP, Sekeres MA, Liang Y. Myelodysplastic syndromes. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2022 Nov 17;8(1):74. doi: 10.1038/s41572-022-00402-5. PMID: 36396662.","Frisch, B., \u0026 Bartl, R. (2012). Atlas of bone marrow pathology (Vol. 15). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Porwit, A., McCullough, J., \u0026 Erber, W. N. (2011). Blood and bone marrow pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationshi